    levels: [
      {
        depth: 1,
        title: "The Hidden Half of the Forest",
        body: `<p>Lift the leaf litter in any old, healthy wood. Beneath your hand is a layer of pale, gauzy thread, finer than spider silk, branching and re-branching through the dark soil like the lace of a slow lightning storm. There may be miles of it under a single footstep. A teaspoon of forest topsoil can contain seven miles of these filaments, woven through every grain of mineral and decaying leaf.</p><p>This is mycelium — the body of a fungus. The mushrooms you can see, the chanterelles and morels and toadstools, are only the fungus's fruit, the fleeting reproductive flourish. The actual organism, the part that lives for decades or centuries, is the network in the soil.</p><p>It eats the dead. It feeds the living. It carries chemical messages between trees that may stand a hundred meters apart. Some single individuals are larger than blue whales. One organism in Oregon spans nearly four square miles. The forest you walk through is not the trees alone. It is the trees, the fungi, and a wet, dark, ancient conversation between them.</p>`,
        pullQuote: "A teaspoon of forest topsoil can contain seven miles of these filaments."
      },
      {
        depth: 2,
        title: "A Different Kind of Body",
        body: `<p>Fungi are not plants. They are also not animals. They form their own kingdom, evolutionarily closer to animals than to anything green, and they make a living in a way no plant or animal does: they grow into their food and digest it from the inside.</p><p>The basic unit of a fungus is the <em>hypha</em> — a single tubular cell, walled in chitin (the same molecule that makes a beetle's shell), often only a few thousandths of a millimeter wide. A hypha grows only at its tip, extending into the soil at speeds of a few hundred micrometers an hour. As it grows, it branches. As it branches, the branches branch. Within days or weeks, a microscopic spore that landed on a fallen log can produce a foaming, three-dimensional lacework of <em>mycelium</em> — the collective mass of hyphae — spreading through wood, leaf litter, or soil.</p><p>This body has no center. It has no head, no heart, no clearly defined edge. Cut it in half and both halves continue. Cut a single hypha and its contents — including organelles, signaling molecules, even nuclei — can flow through it in either direction. In some species, a single mycelium can fuse with another mycelium of its own kind, merging two individuals into one larger network.</p><p>The closest analogy in animal biology is perhaps the nervous system. The closest analogy in human technology is the internet. Neither analogy is right. Mycelium is its own kind of being, and we are only beginning to read its grammar.</p>`,
        pullQuote: "Fungi grow into their food and digest it from the inside."
      },
      {
        depth: 3,
        title: "What Mycelium Does for a Living",
        body: `<p>The world's mycelium does three jobs of planetary importance.</p><p>The first is decomposition. Fungi are the principal decomposers of woody plant material on Earth. The molecule lignin — the rigid polymer that gives wood its strength — is so chemically tough that virtually no animal and very few bacteria can break it down. For roughly forty million years in the Carboniferous, before any organism evolved the enzymes to digest it, dead trees simply accumulated, eventually becoming the world's coal seams. Then, around 300 million years ago, white-rot fungi — including modern descendants like <em>Trametes versicolor</em> and <em>Pleurotus ostreatus</em>, the oyster mushroom — evolved lignin-degrading enzymes called <em>laccases</em> and <em>peroxidases</em>. The age of accumulating coal ended. Recycling began.</p><p>The second is symbiosis. Roughly 90 percent of all land plants form intimate partnerships with fungi at their roots. These partnerships, called <em>mycorrhizas</em> (from Greek <em>mykos</em>, fungus, and <em>rhiza</em>, root), come in two main forms. <em>Ectomycorrhizal</em> fungi, common with pine, oak, beech, and birch, wrap a sheath around the outside of fine roots and extend hyphae into the surrounding soil. <em>Arbuscular mycorrhizal</em> fungi, used by most other plants including most crops, actually penetrate root cells and form tiny tree-like structures (<em>arbuscules</em>) inside them. The fungus delivers water, phosphorus, and nitrogen to the plant. The plant delivers sugars and lipids to the fungus. Neither partner can flourish without the other. This relationship is at least 450 million years old; it may be the alliance that allowed plants to colonize land in the first place.</p><p>The third is connection. Because a single mycorrhizal fungus can simultaneously attach to many trees, it can transfer resources between them. In a series of celebrated experiments beginning in the 1990s, the Canadian ecologist Suzanne Simard injected radioactive carbon (<code>¹⁴C</code>) into birch saplings and recovered it days later in nearby Douglas fir trees, traveling through shared mycorrhizal networks. Older trees, she found, often subsidize younger ones; trees of different species exchange resources seasonally. The popular term for this is the "wood-wide web." The scientific reality is messier and contested, but unmistakably real.</p>`
      },
      {
        depth: 4,
        title: "The Biology of a Network",
        body: `<p>To understand mycelium structurally, it helps to think of it as a fluid topology rather than a fixed body. A mycelial network is constantly remodeling itself: extending hyphae into new resource patches, withdrawing them from depleted zones, fusing branches through a process called <em>anastomosis</em>, and reabsorbing redundant connections to recycle their material. The result is a network whose architecture is, in a precise mathematical sense, optimized for transport. Studies by Mark Fricker at Oxford and Toshiyuki Nakagaki in Japan have shown that fungal networks (and the related slime mold <em>Physarum polycephalum</em>) reliably approximate the shortest path between resource nodes, sometimes more efficiently than human-engineered transit networks.</p><p>Hyphal growth is polarized. Each hyphal tip contains a dense vesicle-supply complex called the <em>Spitzenkörper</em>, which directs the secretion of new cell wall material and the insertion of new membrane. The Spitzenkörper functions as a kind of mobile factory at the leading edge of growth, responsive to chemical gradients in the surrounding substrate. Mycelium grows toward nutrients (positive chemotaxis), away from toxins, and around obstacles in ways that suggest a form of decentralized environmental sensing.</p><p>The genetics are also strange. Many fungi maintain multiple nuclei per cell — often genetically different nuclei, derived from the fusion of mycelia of two different individuals. Some species (the basidiomycetes that produce most familiar mushrooms) routinely live for most of their lives as <em>dikaryons</em>, with two distinct nuclei per cell, only briefly fusing to form a true diploid before meiosis and spore production. This nuclear flexibility allows fungi to mix genetic material in ways that have no clean animal analogue.</p><p>Reproductively, the production of mushrooms is a relatively rare and resource-expensive event. Most fungi exist for the great majority of their lives in purely vegetative form, mycelium only, and produce visible fruiting bodies only when environmental triggers — typically a combination of temperature, moisture, and nutrient depletion — signal that conditions are right for spore release. A single large fruiting body can release billions of spores. The puffball <em>Calvatia gigantea</em> may release seven trillion. Each spore is a potential founder of a new network; the great majority will land somewhere inhospitable and die.</p>`
      },
      {
        depth: 5,
        title: "Mechanisms, Molecules, and the Wood-Wide Web",
        body: `<p>The mechanism of mycorrhizal symbiosis is now understood in considerable molecular detail. The interaction begins with a chemical handshake. Plant roots release <em>strigolactones</em>, a class of carotenoid-derived signaling molecules, into the rhizosphere. Compatible arbuscular mycorrhizal fungi — almost all of which belong to the phylum Glomeromycota, with the model species being <em>Rhizophagus irregularis</em> — perceive these molecules and respond by producing lipochitooligosaccharide signaling molecules called <em>Myc factors</em>, structurally related to the <em>Nod factors</em> used by nitrogen-fixing bacteria in legume nodules. The plant root perceives Myc factors via a receptor-like kinase pathway, triggering a calcium-spiking response in root cells that initiates the molecular program of symbiosis.</p><p>Once inside the root cortex, the fungus differentiates into arbuscules — finely branched, tree-like structures inside individual root cells, where the actual nutrient exchange takes place. Phosphorus, generally as <code>HPO₄²⁻</code> orthophosphate ions, is transported from the fungus to the plant via dedicated plant phosphate transporters (the <em>PT4</em> family in legumes, with orthologs in most crops). In exchange, the plant delivers fixed carbon to the fungus in two forms: sugars (principally hexose) and lipids, the latter discovered to be central only in the 2010s through work by Maria Harrison's lab at the Boyce Thompson Institute.</p><p>The LCO signaling involved in establishing and maintaining the symbiosis is itself an active area of research; recent work on the GRAS-family transcription factors RAM1 and RAD1 has illuminated how plants reprogram their root cells to host the fungal partner without triggering an immune response.</p><p>The "common mycorrhizal network" or CMN — Simard's wood-wide web — is now a contested topic. The original radiocarbon experiments, published by Simard et al. in <em>Nature</em> in 1997, showed bidirectional carbon transfer between Douglas fir (<em>Pseudotsuga menziesii</em>) and paper birch (<em>Betula papyrifera</em>) through shared ectomycorrhizal networks dominated by <em>Rhizopogon</em> species. Subsequent studies have replicated the basic phenomenon many times, but the magnitudes, ecological significance, and adaptive function remain debated. A widely discussed 2023 review by Justine Karst, Melanie Jones, and Jason Hoeksema in <em>Nature Ecology and Evolution</em> argued that several popular claims about CMNs — that they preferentially favor kin, that they constitute a form of "communication" — are not yet supported by the available evidence, and that media coverage has run ahead of the science.</p><p>What is not in dispute is the staggering biomass and metabolic significance of mycorrhizal fungi. A 2023 paper by Heidi Hawkins and colleagues in <em>Current Biology</em> estimated that mycorrhizal fungi transport approximately 13 billion tons of carbon dioxide-equivalent from plants into soils each year — roughly 36 percent of current annual fossil fuel emissions. The world's largest known single fungal individual is a specimen of <em>Armillaria ostoyae</em>, the honey fungus, in the Malheur National Forest in eastern Oregon, covering approximately 9.6 square kilometers (3.7 square miles), weighing an estimated 7,500 to 35,000 tons, and thought to be between 2,400 and 8,650 years old.</p>`
      },
      {
        depth: 6,
        title: "The Frontier of Fungal Intelligence",
        body: `<p>Mycological science has moved with unusual public visibility in the past decade, driven in part by Merlin Sheldrake's <em>Entangled Life</em> (2020), Peter Wohlleben's <em>The Hidden Life of Trees</em> (2015), and Suzanne Simard's autobiographical <em>Finding the Mother Tree</em> (2021). The popular reception has occasionally outrun the data, and the resulting tension between media-friendly narratives and laboratory caution is now itself a major topic of methodological debate.</p><p>Several research frontiers are particularly active. The first is fungal cognition and signaling. Andrew Adamatzky at the University of the West of England has published a series of papers in <em>Royal Society Open Science</em> and <em>Bioelectricity</em> documenting patterned electrical impulses in mycelium of <em>Pleurotus djamor</em>, <em>Ganoderma resinaceum</em>, and other species, with statistical structures he has analogized to language. Whether this constitutes "fungal language" — Adamatzky has identified what he describes as "words" averaging 5.97 spikes per cluster — or simply rhythmic electrochemical activity remains controversial. The skeptical view, articulated by neuroscientists including Lincoln Taiz, is that pattern recognition in noisy electrical traces is not, by itself, evidence of communication. The friendlier view is that mycelial signaling shares more with neural signaling than we are currently equipped to recognize.</p><p>The second frontier is the role of fungi in climate. The Society for the Protection of Underground Networks (SPUN), founded in 2021 by Toby Kiers, Colin Averill, and others, is conducting the first systematic global survey of mycorrhizal biodiversity, with the goal of identifying soil-microbial hotspots for conservation and assessing fungal contribution to global carbon cycling. Early findings suggest that mycorrhizal communities are far more biogeographically varied than previously assumed, and that current soil-conservation policy almost entirely ignores them.</p><p>The third frontier is biomedical and biotechnological. The discovery of psilocybin-producing fungi has generated an enormous wave of clinical research into psychedelic-assisted psychiatry, now being conducted under FDA breakthrough-therapy designation. The fungal endophyte <em>Taxomyces andreanae</em>, isolated from Pacific yew, produces taxol, the breast-cancer chemotherapy. Mycelium-based materials — Ecovative's MycoComposite packaging, Bolt Threads' Mylo leather substitute, the structural mycelium-bonded composites being investigated by NASA for off-world construction — represent a small but growing class of biomaterials made by feeding agricultural waste to species like <em>Ganoderma lucidum</em>.</p><p>The fourth frontier is conceptual. What kind of entity is a mycelium? Philosophers of biology including Peter Godfrey-Smith and ecologists like Lynn Margulis (whose 1967 <em>Journal of Theoretical Biology</em> paper on the origin of eukaryotic cells through endosymbiosis is one of the foundational documents of modern biology) have argued that organisms like mycelium force us to revise our basic categories of individual, agent, and self. A fungus is not one thing in the way a deer is one thing. It is a process of distributed metabolism, networked across a territory, only intermittently expressing itself as visible body. The question of what to call such a being — and what moral and ecological obligations follow from doing so — is, increasingly, not just a scientific question but a political one.</p>`
      }
    ]
